Minister of Cooperative Governance and Traditional Affairs Zweli Mkhize has described the late Winnie Madikizela-Mandela as a revolutionaryÂ  who fought for the country. Mkhize was accompanied by ANC Women's League members to pay tribute to the fallen liberation giant in Soweto on Tuesday morning. Mkhize said the whole country is mourning. "We mourn a revolutionary. A real fighter. We will remember her for her courage." Mkhize said Madikizela-Mandela always put the nation first. ALSO READ: Mourners gather outside the home of #WinnieMandela "Over the years Winnie Madikizela-Mandela would never rest. Because of her role we called her the mother of the nation. She always loved people. She was a warm and loving mother. She was there for the poor." "We are losing the last committed freedom fighters. She was fearless. She never feared to criticize the party. She had passion for the ANC and the youth." LOOK: #WinnieMandela and her iconic fashion Meanwhile EFF leader Julius Malema has arrived to pay tribute to the mother of the nation. Scores of party members are singing outside the Orlando home. Madikizela-Mandela died after a long illness, for which she had been in and out of hospital since the start of the year. She succumbed in the early hours of Monday afternoon surrounded by her family and loved ones. @SthembisoMedia The Star